121.subject: MLSC
121.courseTitle: INTRO TO THE US ARMY I
121.courseDescription: Introduction to the United States Army I. (1-3). Credit 2. Introduction to the United States Army and the Army Reserve Officer Training Corps (ROTC); its purpose in the Army and its advantages; Army customs, courtesies, traditions, and Army values; Army history and individual soldier skills with an emphasis on leadership; includes a leadership laboratory.

122.subject: MLSC
122.courseTitle: INTRO TO THE US ARMY II
122.courseDescription: Introduction to the United States Army II. (1-3). Credit 2. The second half of an introductory two-semester survey of the United States Army; principles of leadership, Army history, management theory and individual soldier skills; emphasis on critical thinking and problem solving skills; foundation for tactical and leadership concepts; includes a leadership laboratory.

221.subject: MLSC
221.courseDescription: Tactics and Leadership Theory I. (2-3). Credit 3. Dimensions of creative and innovative leadership strategies through team dynamics and leadership theories that form the basis of the Army leadership framework (trait and behavior theories); infantry tactics, techniques and procedures; includes a leadership laboratory.

222.subject: MLSC
222.courseDescription: Tactics and Leadership Theory II. (2-3). Credit 3. The second half of a two-semester survey on leadership theory and infantry tactics; emphasis on leading tactical teams in a complex environment; Army planning and orders process; adaptive leadership styles in the context of military operations; case studies on the importance of teamwork and tactics in real-world scenarios; includes a leadership laboratory.

321.subject: MLSC
321.courseDescription: Adaptive Leadership and Tactical Operations I. (3-1). Credit 3. Theoretical and practical application of adaptive leadership as it relates to planning, executing and evaluating complex tactical operations; ability to assess risk, ethical decision-making, managing people and critical thinking skills in a tactical environment; includes a leadership laboratory.

322.subject: MLSC
322.courseDescription: Adaptive Leadership and Tactical Operations II. (3-1). Credit 3. The second half of a two-semester survey on adaptive leadership and tactical operations; ethical decision-making, planning, executing and evaluating military operations at a tactical level; preparation to attend the Leadership, Development and Assessment Course (LDAC) for the Army's commissioning process; includes a leadership laboratory.

421.subject: MLSC
421.courseDescription: The Army Officer and the Profession of Arms I. (3-1). Credit 3. Advanced study, research and practical application of Army training, operations and doctrine; the military as a profession, functioning as a member of a staff, and officership; law of land warfare, principles of war, and rules of engagement and their application; duties and responsibilities of a Second Lieutenant in the United States Army; includes a leadership laboratory.

422.subject: MLSC
422.courseDescription: The Army Officer and the Profession of Arms II. (3-1). Credit 3. Dynamics of leadership in a complex world; cultural awareness, terrorism, non-governmental organizations, and operational security; off-site battlefield analysis and application of military concepts; maintaining an ethical climate in an organization, military support structures, and equal opportunity; duties and responsibilities of a Second Lieutenant in the United States Army; includes a leadership laboratory.

485.subject: MLSC
485.courseDescription: Directed Studies.  Credit 1 to 3. Directed study of problems in the field of military science. Prerequisite: Junior or senior classification with approval of department head.

489.subject: MLSC
489.courseDescription: Special Topics in...  Credit 1 to 4. Selected topics in an identified field of military science. May be repeated for credit.

491.subject: MLSC
491.courseDescription: Research. Credit 1 to 4. Research conducted under the direction of a faculty member in military science. May be taken three times for credit. Prerequisite: Junior or senior classification or approval of instructor.
